:["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Giffard was born about 24 June 1287, in Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. He married Aveline de Courtenay before 1311. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in April 1323, in Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"about 24 June 1287–April 1323 or May 1323":"umbes 24. juuni 1287–aprill 1